ne-grained experiences of Newark residents, Krasovic reveals that this liberalism was rooted in an ethic of experimentation and local knowledge. He illustrates this with stories of innovation within government offices, the dynamic encounters between local activists and state agencies, and the unlikely alliances among nominal enemies. Krasovic makes clear that postwar liberalism’s eventual fate had as much to do with the experiments waged in Newark as it did with the violence that rocked the city in the summer of 1967.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommunity activistszNew JerseyzNewark. 0aLiberalismzUnited States. 0aRace riotszNew JerseyzNewark. 0aSocial actionzNew JerseyzNewarkxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  anewark, city, urban, integration, segregation, housing, race, prejudice, discrimination, violence, riots, protest, politics, history, nonfiction, liberalism, new jersey, social policy, activism, government, political science, police department, community relations, war on poverty, mayor, black, great society, lyndon b johnson, neighborhood, law enforcement, welfare state.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978022635279440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226352824423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226352824/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles